  <section id="section-7">
    <h2>7. Strategy 6 — Email list nurture and reactivation</h2>

    <div class="strategy-card">
      <div class="sc-header">
        <span class="sc-num">06</span>
        <span class="sc-title">Email List Nurture and Reactivation</span>
      </div>
      <div class="sc-body">
        <div class="sc-stats">
          <div class="sc-stat"><span class="label">Upfront Cost</span><span class="val">Email platform</span></div>
          <div class="sc-stat"><span class="label">Ongoing Effort</span><span class="val">Medium</span></div>
          <div class="sc-stat"><span class="label">Time to First Lead</span><span class="val">Immediate</span></div>
          <div class="sc-stat"><span class="label">Scales With</span><span class="val">List quality</span></div>
        </div>
        <p>If you already have an email list — even a small one — the highest-return lead generation strategy is often not adding new subscribers but converting existing subscribers more effectively. Nurture sequences (automated email series) build trust and present offers at the right moment. Reactivation campaigns re-engage subscribers who have gone cold. Broadcast emails to your existing list generate leads for new offers without any additional traffic cost.</p>
        <p><strong>Why it is the highest-ROI strategy for people with an existing list:</strong> You have already paid for these subscribers — through time, ad spend, or effort. A subscriber who has not bought yet is not a failed lead; they are a relationship that has not reached the right moment. A well-structured nurture sequence extends the conversion window across weeks or months rather than demanding a purchase decision at the moment of opt-in.</p>
        <p><strong>What effective nurture looks like:</strong> The first email delivers the lead magnet and introduces you. Emails 2–5 provide value — teaching, sharing stories, demonstrating expertise — without selling. Email 6 onwards introduces the offer in the context of what the subscriber has already learned. Reactivation sequences reach dormant subscribers with a compelling reason to re-engage before permanently removing them from the active list.</p>
        <p><strong>Best for:</strong> Anyone who already has at least 100 email subscribers. Also relevant immediately for new list builders — the nurture sequence should be built before you drive traffic, not after.</p>
        <div class="sc-tools"><strong>Supporting tools:</strong> Any email marketing platform (ConvertKit, MailerLite, GetResponse, AWeber) — see our <a href="/blog/lead-generation-software/">lead generation software guide</a> for a full comparison of email platform options</div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section id="section-8">
    <h2>8. Strategy 7 — Partnerships and joint ventures</h2>

    <div class="strategy-card">
      <div class="sc-header">
        <span class="sc-num">07</span>
        <span class="sc-title">Partnerships and Joint Ventures</span>
      </div>
      <div class="sc-body">
        <div class="sc-stats">
          <div class="sc-stat"><span class="label">Upfront Cost</span><span class="val">Low</span></div>
          <div class="sc-stat"><span class="label">Ongoing Effort</span><span class="val">Medium</span></div>
          <div class="sc-stat"><span class="label">Time to First Lead</span><span class="val">Weeks</span></div>
          <div class="sc-stat"><span class="label">Scales With</span><span class="val">Network quality</span></div>
        </div>
        <p>You partner with other list owners or content creators who share a complementary audience. In a joint venture (JV), both parties promote each other's offers to their respective lists — each gets exposure to a new warm audience at zero ad cost. In a cross-promotion, one party promotes the other's offer in exchange for a commission or a reciprocal send. In a guest content arrangement, you contribute content to another creator's platform and capture leads from their audience.</p>
        <p><strong>Why it is the most scalable free strategy:</strong> A JV with a list owner who has 10,000 subscribers delivers more leads in one email send than months of solo organic prospecting. The leads are warm because they are arriving via a trusted recommendation from someone they already follow. Conversion rates on JV traffic consistently outperform cold traffic from paid channels.</p>
        <p><strong>The access problem:</strong> Established list owners receive many JV requests and prioritise partners who have something valuable to offer in return — either a comparable list size, a genuinely complementary offer, or a strong track record. Beginners typically need to build a list of at least 500–1,000 engaged subscribers before most JV partners will consider a reciprocal arrangement.</p>
        <p><strong>Best for:</strong> People who have already built a functional list and want to accelerate growth through borrowed audiences. Also the right long-term networking goal for anyone in the affiliate marketing space — the connections formed through JV relationships often become the most durable traffic sources.</p>
        <div class="sc-tools"><strong>Supporting tools:</strong> Email marketing platform (for sending and tracking JV broadcasts), basic outreach tracking (a spreadsheet is sufficient at small scale)</div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

