  <section id="section-10">
    <h2>10. Stacking strategies: what to add once the primary is working</h2>

    <p>Running a single strategy until it produces consistent, measurable lead flow is the prerequisite for adding a second. Stacking strategies before validating the first one fragments attention and makes it impossible to know what is driving results.</p>

    <p>Once your primary strategy produces at least 10–20 leads per week consistently, the right second strategy to add depends on which limitation you are hitting.</p>

    <div class="stack-box">
      <h3>Strategy stacking by limitation</h3>
      <div class="stack-row">
        <span class="stack-phase">Ceiling: Time</span>
        <span class="stack-desc">If your organic prospecting is working but you are hitting your daily time limit: add paid email traffic (Strategy 3) to run parallel to your organic activity. The paid channel fills the funnel while you continue relationship-building at the pace you can sustain.</span>
      </div>
      <div class="stack-row">
        <span class="stack-phase">Ceiling: Audience</span>
        <span class="stack-desc">If paid traffic is working but you are seeing audience fatigue (declining conversion rates from the same sources): add a joint venture or referral channel (Strategies 5 &amp; 7) to access fresh audiences through trusted introductions.</span>
      </div>
      <div class="stack-row">
        <span class="stack-phase">Ceiling: Cost</span>
        <span class="stack-desc">If paid advertising is producing leads but the cost per lead is too high: add a content marketing strategy (Strategy 1) to build organic search traffic that reduces your blended lead cost over time.</span>
      </div>
      <div class="stack-row">
        <span class="stack-phase">Ceiling: Speed</span>
        <span class="stack-desc">If your content marketing is building momentum but you need leads now: run a parallel paid email traffic campaign (Strategy 3) while your organic content continues to mature.</span>
      </div>
      <div class="stack-row">
        <span class="stack-phase">Next layer: Always</span>
        <span class="stack-desc">Regardless of your primary strategy, email list nurture (Strategy 6) should be running from day one. It is not a separate strategy to add later — it is the follow-up infrastructure that determines what happens to every lead your other strategies generate.</span>
      </div>
    </div>

    <p>The practical outcome for most online business builders running the OLSP system is a two-strategy stack: organic Facebook prospecting (Strategy 2) as the primary relationship channel, combined with paid email traffic (Strategy 3) for volume. Email nurture (Strategy 6) runs underneath both, converting leads into customers over a 7–21 day sequence. This three-layer system — relationship prospecting, paid traffic, and email automation — produces a predictable and sustainable lead pipeline for most affiliate offers.</p>

    <p>For tool recommendations to support any of these strategies, see our <a href="/blog/best-lead-generation-tools/">curated tool picks guide</a> and our full <a href="/blog/lead-generation-software/">lead generation software comparison</a>.</p>
  </section>

  <section id="faq">
    <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

    <FaqItem question="What is the best lead generation strategy for beginners?">
      <p>For most beginners, Facebook group organic prospecting is the best starting strategy because it requires no budget, produces warm leads through relationship-building, and gives immediate feedback on your messaging. The limitation is time — expect 2–6 weeks before consistent leads and 3–6 months before a reliable weekly volume. Once you have a working message and a tested landing page, adding paid email traffic significantly accelerates list growth.</p>
    </FaqItem>

    <FaqItem question="How many lead generation strategies should I run at once?">
      <p>One primary strategy at a time until you have at least 100 leads and clear conversion data. Running multiple strategies in parallel before validating any of them means you cannot tell what is working or why. The most common beginner mistake is hopping between channels — trying Facebook groups for two weeks, then solo ads, then SEO — without giving any single strategy enough time to produce meaningful data. Pick one, run it for 60–90 days, measure the results, then add a second channel to stack on the first.</p>
    </FaqItem>

    <FaqItem question="What is the fastest lead generation strategy?">
      <p>Paid email traffic (solo ads or traffic rotators) is the fastest — leads typically arrive within 24–72 hours of purchase, assuming a working landing page. The trade-off is cost: you pay per click, and the leads are colder than relationship-built leads. For sustainable long-term results, paid traffic works best when used to build an email list you then nurture — not to send cold prospects directly to a sales offer.</p>
    </FaqItem>

    <FaqItem question="What is the cheapest lead generation strategy?">
      <p>Organic content marketing (SEO) and organic social prospecting (Facebook groups, community engagement) have the lowest cost — both require time rather than money. The lead cost approaches zero at scale, but the time-to-first-lead is weeks to months rather than hours. For someone with no budget, one of these two strategies is the only viable starting point.</p>
    </FaqItem>

    <FaqItem question="What is the difference between a lead generation strategy and a lead generation tactic?">
      <p>A strategy is a sustained channel commitment — "we will build our list primarily through Facebook group organic prospecting" is a strategy. A tactic is a specific action within that strategy — "post a value-focused comment in three groups every morning" is a tactic. Changing tactics within a working strategy is normal optimisation. Abandoning a strategy before it has had time to produce data is the error that keeps most beginners stuck.</p>
    </FaqItem>

    <FaqItem question="How long does it take for a lead generation strategy to start working?">
      <p>It depends on the channel. Paid traffic produces leads within 24–72 hours. Organic social prospecting typically produces first meaningful conversations within 1–3 weeks of consistent daily activity. SEO content marketing typically takes 3–12 months to produce significant organic traffic. For most beginners, the realistic expectation is 30–60 days of consistent effort before having enough data to evaluate whether a strategy is working for their specific offer.</p>
    </FaqItem>
  </section>

